            "content": "## Context\n\nChat pinning ships today as `chats.pinnedAt` ŌĆö a `timestamptz` **column on the chat row** (`apps/api/src/db/schema/chats.ts:51-53`) ŌĆö ordered pinned-first via `chats_owner_pinned_updated_idx`, toggled through `PATCH /api/v1/chats/:id {pinned}`, and rendered as a `PINNED` group in the chat list (`apps/web/lib/services/chat/queries.ts:181,201`). Projects have no pinning: `ProjectListSidebar` shows a disabled \"Pin ŌĆö coming soon\" placeholder (`apps/web/app/(chat)/components/project-list-sidebar/index.tsx:80-96`).\n\nA column on the item row encodes \"the item is pinned\" and works only because a chat has exactly one owner (`chats.ownerUserId` is the tenant boundary). It cannot encode \"pinned by user X but not user Y.\" Per-user pinning ŌĆö and, later, true multi-user chats where several users each keep their own pinned set ŌĆö requires pin state to live in a per-user relation.\n\nThe target UX is fixed by the design system (`AppShell.dc.html`): the main rail carries a single \"Pinned\" section that mixes chats and projects in one flat, pin-recency-ordered list (`llame-common.js` `PINNED = [{type,id,label,icon,href}, ŌĆ”]`), and each item list keeps its own \"Pinned\" group. This is a general per-user *favorites index* that references chats and projects, not two parallel pin features.\n\nConstraints from the codebase: RLS-in-the-datastore with `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` is a hard invariant (`apps/api/CLAUDE.md`); every request runs inside `TenantDbService.runAs`; migrations are drizzle-kit-generated with hand-appended `FORCE` (0011/0018 precedent); REST is resource-oriented, no RPC verb handles, DTO in / explicit response type out.\n\n## Goals / Non-Goals\n\n**Goals:**\n\n- Move pin state off the item row into a per-user, cross-type pin index.\n- One HTTP resource for pin/unpin/list, symmetric in how it addresses items.\n- Datastore-enforced per-user isolation; a user can only pin what they can access.\n- One unified pinned list for the rail; viewer-scoped pin state for each item list's \"Pinned\" group.\n- A strongly-typed, additively-extensible item-type enumeration.\n\n**Non-Goals:**\n\n- **True multi-user chats.** This change is the per-user pin *substrate* that de-risks that epic; it does not add chat participants, rewrite chat RLS from owner-only to membership, fan out message sender attribution, or change run ownership. The write-time accessibility check is the single seam that later widens.\n- Manual drag ordering of pins (a `position` column). Order is `pinned_at DESC` only.\n- Backfilling or preserving existing chat pins. Existing `chats.pinnedAt` data is dropped.\n- Pinning any item type beyond chat and project in this slice.\n\n## Decisions\n\n### D1 ŌĆö Single polymorphic `pins` table (not per-type tables)\n\n```\npin_item_type = pgEnum('pin_item_type', ['chat','project'])\n\npins (\n  user_id    text  ŌåÆ users.id  ON DELETE CASCADE,   -- text: NextAuth users.id is text\n  item_type  pin_item_type NOT NULL,\n  item_id    uuid  NOT NULL,                         -- polymorphic: no cross-type FK\n  pinned_at  timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n  PRIMARY KEY (user_id, item_type, item_id)\n)\nindex pins_user_pinned_idx ON (user_id, pinned_at DESC)   -- the rail's ORDER BY\n```\n\nThe rail's primary read is one ordered, mixed-type list. A polymorphic table produces it as a single indexed scan (`WHERE user_id=? ORDER BY pinned_at DESC`); per-type tables (`chat_pins`, `project_pins`) would require `UNION ALL` + re-sort + paginate across N tables, degrading with every new pinnable type. The composite PK gives idempotent pin/unpin and point-lookup joins for viewer-scoped pin state.\n\n**Alternative ŌĆö per-type pin tables.** Buys a real FK per type and cascade-on-delete. Rejected: it fights the mixed-list read (the design's core surface) and multiplies tables per pinnable type. The integrity it buys is recovered by D3 (write gate) and D4 (hydrate-time filter) without a table per type.\n\n### D2 ŌĆö Item type + id in the path; idempotent `PUT`/`DELETE`\n\nA pin has no mutable field (only existence + a server-set `pinned_at`), so it is a resource addressed by its natural key `(itemType, itemId)`:\n\n```\nGET    /api/v1/pins                     ŌåÆ caller's pinned items, mixed, pinned_at DESC\nPUT    /api/v1/pins/:itemType/:itemId   ŌåÆ pin   (idempotent)\nDELETE /api/v1/pins/:itemType/:itemId   ŌåÆ unpin (idempotent)\n```\n\n`PUT` (upsert `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING`) and `DELETE` are both idempotent, both key the item in the path, neither takes a body. This resolves the asymmetry of a `POST {itemType,itemId}` create paired with path-keyed delete. `:itemType` is validated against the enum by the DTO/pipe; `:itemId` gets `ParseUUIDPipe`. No `/chats/:id/pin` verb handle ŌĆö that would re-split per type and violate the repo's no-RPC-handle rule.\n\n**Alternative ŌĆö `POST /pins` with body.** Rejected per the above (asymmetric, and a pin has no body worth carrying).\n\n### D3 ŌĆö Per-user RLS + write-time accessibility gate\n\nPolicies (FORCE, hand-appended in the migration):\n\n- `SELECT` / `DELETE` USING: `user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true)`. Under `runAsPublic` (`current_user = ''`) nothing matches ŌåÆ pins are never exposed on the public path.\n- `INSERT` WITH CHECK: `user_id = current_user AND` a per-type accessibility subquery, mirroring the chatŌåÆproject filing gate (`chats.ts:85`):\n  ```sql\n  user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true) AND (\n    (item_type = 'chat'    AND item_id IN (SELECT id FROM chats    WHERE owner_user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true)))\n    OR (item_type = 'project' AND item_id IN (SELECT id FROM projects WHERE owner_user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true)))\n  )\n  ```\n  Each subquery runs under the referenced table's own RLS, so \"accessible\" is exactly \"the caller can see it.\" No recursion (chats/projects never scan `pins`). When multi-user chats arrive, only the `chat` branch's predicate widens (owner-or-participant); the pin model is untouched.\n\n### D4 ŌĆö Read-time hydration is also the orphan/stale filter\n\n`GET /pins` scans `pins` for the user, then batch-loads titles/names by type (chat ids ŌåÆ `chats`, project ids ŌåÆ `projects`) under RLS, preserving `pinned_at DESC`. A pin whose item was deleted or is no longer accessible returns no title under RLS and is simply dropped from the result. This makes graceful degradation the default and removes the need for `AFTER DELETE` cleanup triggers (which the codebase treats as migration exceptions). No cross-type FK is therefore needed (D1). A periodic sweep can be added later if the table accumulates dead rows, but is not required for correctness.\n\n### D5 ŌĆö Viewer-scoped `pinnedAt` on item lists via per-caller LEFT JOIN\n\nItem lists surface pin state without a second endpoint: chat/project list reads add `LEFT JOIN pins p ON p.user_id = :me AND p.item_type = '<type>' AND p.item_id = <resource>.id` (PK-indexed point lookup) and project `p.pinned_at` into the response DTO as a viewer-scoped field. The chat list's existing grouping already buckets on `pinnedAt` (`queries.ts:201`) ŌĆö its shape is unchanged; only the column's *source* moves from the chat row to the join. Ordering stays `updated_at DESC` (chats) / `created_at DESC` (projects); the frontend lifts pinned rows into the \"Pinned\" group, so the SQL no longer needs a pinned-first sort ŌĆö `chats_owner_pinned_updated_idx` is dropped, `chats_owner_updated_idx` remains.\n\n### D6 ŌĆö Drop-and-replace migration, no backfill\n\nPer the change's scope: `DROP COLUMN chats.pinnedAt` + drop `chats_owner_pinned_updated_idx`; `CREATE TYPE pin_item_type` + `CREATE TABLE pins` + index + policies + `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY`. Existing pins are discarded. This keeps the migration a plain generated forward migration plus the hand-appended `FORCE` (no manual `UPDATE`/`INSERT` backfill block).\n\n## Risks / Trade-offs\n\n- **No DB FK on `item_id` (polymorphic).** ŌåÆ Referential validity is enforced at write by D3's accessibility gate; dangling pins are filtered at read by D4. Acceptable because pins are soft references, not integrity-critical relations.\n- **Viewer-scoped `pinnedAt` is a per-caller derived field on a shared resource.** ŌåÆ Documented as viewer-scoped and sourced only from the authenticated caller's join; never leaks another user's pin state. A cache of a chat/project list is per-user already (owner-scoped today), so no new cache-key hazard.\n- **Dropping `chats.pinnedAt` is BREAKING for `apps/web`.** ŌåÆ Only `apps/web` consumes it, updated in the same change; the removed `PATCH /chats {pinned}` field and the new `/pins` service land together. No external clients (SDK codegen is deferred).\n- **`PUT` with an empty body to create a resource is slightly unusual.** ŌåÆ Justified: the resource genuinely has no client-supplied data; idempotent upsert is the correct semantic and keeps the surface symmetric (D2).\n- **Enum widening later needs a migration.** ŌåÆ Accepted; a new `ALTER TYPE ... ADD VALUE` + a new accessibility branch is the intended additive path and matches how `run_status` / `chat_visibility` evolve.\n\n## Migration Plan\n\n1. Schema change in `apps/api/src/db/schema`: add `pin_item_type` enum + `pins` table (`schema/pins.ts`), remove `pinnedAt` and its index from `chats.ts`.\n2. `pnpm --filter api db:generate`; hand-append `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` on `pins` to the generated SQL and record it in the `apps/api/CLAUDE.md` \"hand-authored exceptions\" list.\n3. Deploy is forward-only. Rollback = restore the column-based pin (revert migration); acceptable because no pin data is preserved either direction and the feature is internal.\n4. Ship API + web together (the `PATCH /chats {pinned}` removal and the rail/list wiring are one release).\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- None blocking. Enum widening for future pinnable types (artifact, knowledge space, memory) is deliberately deferred to when those entities exist and their accessibility predicate is known.\n",
