            "new_string": "  Each subquery runs under the referenced table's own RLS, so \"accessible\" is exactly \"the caller can see it.\" No recursion (chats/projects never scan `pins`). When multi-user chats arrive, only the `chat` branch's predicate widens (owner-or-participant); the pin model is untouched.\n\n  **\"Accessible\" = owned** for this slice: a user may pin only items they own. A non-owned *public* chat is deliberately **not** pinnable ŌĆö allowing the write without a matching read would create an invisible dead pin (the hydration join runs under the caller's authenticated RLS, and `chats_public_read` only matches the no-identity `runAsPublic` path, `chats.ts:93-96`), and \"pin\" means \"keep my own thing handy,\" not \"bookmark a shared link.\" Bookmarking shared/public content is a separate future decision.\n\n- **Write-denial ŌåÆ HTTP:** an inaccessible or nonexistent `item_id` fails the `WITH CHECK` and surfaces as `42501` (RLS). The service maps it to `NotFoundException` with no existence oracle ŌĆö exactly the filing-gate precedent (`chats.service.ts:127-164`), never a `500`. Pins has no FK on `item_id`, so `23503` cannot arise from the item (only the server-derived `user_id` FK, which always exists).\n\n### D4 ŌĆö Read-time hydration into per-type cards; also the orphan/stale filter\n\n`GET /pins` scans `pins` for the user, then batch-loads each type's **reference card** (chat ids ŌåÆ `{id,title}` from `chats`; project ids ŌåÆ `{id,name}` from `projects`) under RLS, preserving `pinned_at DESC`, and assembles the `PinnedItemResponse` wrapper (D2). A pin whose item was deleted or is no longer accessible yields no card under RLS and is simply dropped. This makes graceful degradation the default and removes the need for `AFTER DELETE` cleanup triggers (migration exceptions in this codebase). No cross-type FK is therefore needed (D1). A periodic sweep can be added later if the table accumulates dead rows, but is not required for correctness. Cross-feature reads here are direct Drizzle reads against the shared `../db/schema` under RLS ŌĆö not `ChatsService`/`ProjectsService` calls ŌĆö so no `PinsModule`Ōåö`ChatsModule` import and no circular dependency (matches how `chats-repository.ts` imports the whole schema and joins freely; module imports in this repo are for *behavior*, not table reads).\n\n### D5 ŌĆö Pins is the sole source of pin truth; the client composes (no viewer field on item lists)\n\nChat and project **list** responses carry **no** pin information ŌĆö no `pinnedAt` field, no join. `pins` is a self-contained subsystem and its `GET /pins` is the single source of pin state. Two client surfaces compose the one `usePins()` query:\n\n- **Rail** renders directly from `GET /pins` ŌĆö the embedded `RefCard` gives title/name (and later per-type icon/color), the client derives icon + href from `itemType`. This covers pinned items even when they fall outside the loaded list window.\n- **Per-list \"Pinned\" group** is built on the client by intersecting the item list (`useChats()`/`useProjects()`) with the pinned id-set from `usePins()`, ordered by `pins.pinnedAt`. The rich rows (`lastMessage`, run `status`) come from the **list** cache ŌĆö their canonical home, kept fresh by the list's own streaming invalidation ŌĆö never from the pins cache.\n\nThis is why the embedded card is lean (D2): the pins cache holds only render-stable fields, so its staleness surface is bounded to explicit edits (rename/recolor/delete/pin) ŌĆö the exact invalidations in D5a ŌĆö and never collides with streaming. Optimistic pin toggle mutates **only** the pins cache (add/remove a ref), and the row re-buckets instantly; no patching a `pinnedAt` inside the list cache.\n\nThe chat list SQL loses its pinned-first sort entirely: `findByOwner` orders by `updated_at DESC` only, `chats_owner_pinned_updated_idx` is dropped, `chats_owner_updated_idx` remains. This supersedes an earlier draft that put a viewer-scoped `pinnedAt` on the list responses; that mechanism is rejected because it leaves a pin field on the chat contract and re-adds a per-read join for state the client can compose from the pins query it already holds.\n\n### D5a ŌĆö Cache invalidation\n\nAny mutation that changes an item's card fields or its existence invalidates `pinQueryKeys.list()`: chat rename/delete, project rename/(future recolor)/delete, and pin/unpin. Pin/unpin additionally invalidates the affected item's list query so the per-list \"Pinned\" group re-buckets. Server-side deletion self-heals (D4 drops non-hydratable pins); invalidation only governs *when* the client refetches.",
            "old_string": "  Each subquery runs under the referenced table's own RLS, so \"accessible\" is exactly \"the caller can see it.\" No recursion (chats/projects never scan `pins`). When multi-user chats arrive, only the `chat` branch's predicate widens (owner-or-participant); the pin model is untouched.\n\n### D4 ŌĆö Read-time hydration is also the orphan/stale filter\n\n`GET /pins` scans `pins` for the user, then batch-loads titles/names by type (chat ids ŌåÆ `chats`, project ids ŌåÆ `projects`) under RLS, preserving `pinned_at DESC`. A pin whose item was deleted or is no longer accessible returns no title under RLS and is simply dropped from the result. This makes graceful degradation the default and removes the need for `AFTER DELETE` cleanup triggers (which the codebase treats as migration exceptions). No cross-type FK is therefore needed (D1). A periodic sweep can be added later if the table accumulates dead rows, but is not required for correctness.\n\n### D5 ŌĆö Viewer-scoped `pinnedAt` on item lists via per-caller LEFT JOIN\n\nItem lists surface pin state without a second endpoint: chat/project list reads add `LEFT JOIN pins p ON p.user_id = :me AND p.item_type = '<type>' AND p.item_id = <resource>.id` (PK-indexed point lookup) and project `p.pinned_at` into the response DTO as a viewer-scoped field. The chat list's existing grouping already buckets on `pinnedAt` (`queries.ts:201`) ŌĆö its shape is unchanged; only the column's *source* moves from the chat row to the join. Ordering stays `updated_at DESC` (chats) / `created_at DESC` (projects); the frontend lifts pinned rows into the \"Pinned\" group, so the SQL no longer needs a pinned-first sort ŌĆö `chats_owner_pinned_updated_idx` is dropped, `chats_owner_updated_idx` remains.",
